Decided to dig a bit further. The first cell on the first row has the following style:

```json
{
  "numFmt": "@",
  "font": {
    "size": 11,
    "color": {
      "indexed": 9
    },
    "name": "Calibri"
  },
  "border": {
    "left": {
      "style": "thin",
      "color": {
        "indexed": 11
      }
    },
    "right": {
      "style": "thin",
      "color": {
        "indexed": 11
      }
    },
    "top": {
      "style": "thin",
      "color": {
        "indexed": 11
      }
    },
    "bottom": {
      "style": "thin",
      "color": {
        "indexed": 11
      }
    }
  },
  "fill": {
    "type": "pattern",
    "pattern": "solid",
    "fgColor": {
      "indexed": 10
    }
  },
  "alignment": {
    "vertical": "bottom"
  }
}
```

What I notice is the colours are using indexed values, rather than hex values. I could not see any indication of indexed colour support in the docs and no evidence that exceljs tries converting the indexed values to hex values.

Extracting the source xlsx I do see an xl/styles.xml document. which contains the following block:

```xml
	<colors>
		<indexedColors>
			<rgbColor rgb="ff000000" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ffffffff" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ffff0000" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ff00ff00" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ff0000ff" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ffffff00" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ffff00ff" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ff00ffff" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ff000000" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ffffffff" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ff3f6797" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ffaaaaaa" />
		</indexedColors>
	</colors>
```

The colour as indexed 10 is "3f6797", which is what is shown in the original.

In the output file, the indexed colours are indeed different, with no reference to colour '3f6797':

```xml
		<indexedColors>
			<rgbColor rgb="ff000000" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ffffffff" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ffff0000" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ff00ff00" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ff0000ff" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ffffff00" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ffff00ff" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ff00ffff" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ff000000" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ffffffff" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ffff0000" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ff00ff00" />
			<rgbColor rgb="ffaaaaaa" />
		</indexedColors>
```

Taking the styles file from the original and using it in the output results in the correct colours being used.

+1
Mine is similarly because the original file is using indexed colors that totally disappear from the styles file in the output.

@ajmas do you know if there's a nice-ish way to script the "xl/styles.xml" workaround without unzipping/rezipping (e.g. using adm-zip)?
